<section id="forms">

	<div class="container">

		<h2>Forms</h2>

		<p>Forms in Watercolor are pretty simple, yet tremendously flexible. Forms fields should be marked up as <code>div</code> elements with a <code>field</code> class. Form buttons should be enclosed in a <code>div</code> with a <code>buttons</code> class. With this basic markup and a little bit of help from the form @@mixins you can display your forms in a variety of ways.</p>

	</div>

</section>

<section id="mixins">

	<div class="container">

		<h3>Form Mixins</h3>
		<p>The form @@mixins are defined in <code>modules/form.scss</code> and provide @@mixins for styling forms depending on your site's needs.</p>

		<table>

			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th style="width: 25%">mixin</th>
					<th>description</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>

			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td><code>field-block</code></td>
					<td>Each form field is displayed on a separate line, with the label above the field. This is the default form type.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><code>field-inline</code></td>
					<td>Each form field is displayed in an inline manner, with the label above the field.  The buttons are displayed below the form on a separate line.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><code>field-align</code></td>
					<td>Each form field is displayed on a separate line, with the field labels aligned to the left of the field.  The buttons are displayed below the form on a separate line.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><code>field-hint</code></td>
					<td>Mixin to set up the form hint element.</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>

		</table>

	</div>

</section>

<section id="partials" class="container">

	<h3>Form Partials</h3>
	<p>A form partial is provided in <code>partials/form.scss</code> and uses the standard @@mixins to set up the standard classes used in form markup. You can include this partial in your project, or code your own if you prefer a different style.</p>

	<pre><code class="language-css">.field {
	@@include field-block;
}
.hint {
	@@include hint;
}</code></pre>

</section>

<section id="standard-markup" class="container">

	<h3>Standard Markup</h3>
	<p>The following is an example of the standard markup of a Watercolor form. The highlights are that fields need a containing div with class <code>field</code>, and you can add hints on each field to better aid users in completing your form.</p>

	<div class="example">

		<form>

			<fieldset>

				<legend>Legend</legend>

				<div class="field">
					<label>Field 1:</label>
					<input type="text" />
					<span class="hint">Form hint</span>
				</div>

				<div class="field">
					<label>Field 2:</label>
					<input type="text" />
					<span class="hint">Form hint</span>
				</div>

			</fieldset>

			<p>
				<input type="submit" /> <input type="reset" value="Reset" />
			</p>

		</form>

	</div>

	<pre class="example-code"><code class="language-markup">&lt;form&gt;
   &lt;fieldset&gt;
      &lt;legend&gt;Legend&lt;/legend&gt;
      &lt;div class="field"&gt;
         &lt;label&gt;Field 1:&lt;/label&gt;
         &lt;input type="text" /&gt;
         &lt;span class="hint"&gt;Form hint&lt;/span&gt;
      &lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class="field"&gt;
         &lt;label&gt;Field 2:&lt;/label&gt;
         &lt;input type="text" /&gt;
         &lt;span class="hint"&gt;Form hint&lt;/span&gt;
      &lt;/div&gt;
   &lt;/fieldset&gt;
   &lt;p&gt;
      &lt;input type="submit" /&gt;
      &lt;input type="reset" value="Reset" /&gt;
   &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;</code></pre>

</section>


<section id="basic-form" class="container">

		<h3>Basic Block Form</h3>
		<p>This is a basic Watercolor form, which is styled by default in block layout. All below examples will use this same HTML markup, but with changes in the CSS. <code>fieldset</code> elements aren't required, but are included for the sake of these examples. Each form field is enclosed in a <code>div</code> element with <code>field</code> class. Form buttons are enclosed in a <code>div</code> element with <code>buttons</code> class. Each field can also have an optional <code>span</code> with class <code>hint</code> that pops up a field hint when the field is focused, and turns red if the field is invalid.</p>

		<div class="example">

			<form>

				<fieldset>

					<legend>Account Information</legend>

					<div class="field">
						<label>Email:</label>
						<input type="email" placeholder="user@domain.com" required />
						<span class="hint">Email address is required and must be in the format: user@@domain.com</span>
					</div>

					<div class="field">
						<label>Password:</label>
						<input type="password" placeholder="Password" required />
						<span class="hint">Password is required</span>
					</div>

				</fieldset>

				<fieldset>

					<legend>Contact Information</legend>

					<div class="field">
						<label>First Name:</label>
						<input type="text" placeholder="First Name" value="" />
						<span class="hint">Please enter your first name</span>
					</div>

					<div class="field">
						<label>Last Name:</label>
						<input type="text" placeholder="Last Name" value="" />
						<span class="hint">Please enter your last name</span>
					</div>

					<div class="field">
						<label>Telephone #:</label>
						<input type="tel" placeholder="847-867-5309" />
						<span class="hint">Please enter your telephone number</span>
					</div>

					<div class="field">
						<label>Website:</label>
						<input type="url" placeholder="http://domain.com" />
						<span class="hint">Please enter your website address in the format: http://domain.com</span>
					</div>

				</fieldset>

				<p>
					<input type="submit" /> <input type="reset" value="Reset" />
				</p>

			</form>

		</div>

		<pre class="example-code"><code class="language-markup">&lt;form&gt;
   &lt;fieldset&gt;
      &lt;legend&gt;Account Information&lt;/legend&gt;
      &lt;div class="field"&gt;
